1 Introduction
Our goal is to use fMRI data to predict a viewer’s emotions while watching a certain TV show in
this lab. We will be doing this by looking at the left and right hemispheres of the viewer’s brain
and analyzing and predicting what values are the most appropriate to classify the viewer’s
emotions during a certain time of the show. This sort of research is important for many different
areas of life, such as predicting what sort of purchases a consumer will make or for hospital
records to determine how effective different types of treatment are to a patient.
In order to build an accurate predictor, we will be using a linear approach to predict these values,
as well as using a machine learning approach using a training set to improve predictions as the
“machine” is given more values, and finally a non-linear approach. By analyzing the results of
these 3 different prediction methods, we can hope to build a predictor with as little error as
possible. This will be important to determine what sort of emotions can be triggered in the
viewer’s mind during certain parts of the show and how to retain their interest in the show.

3) Figures 4 and 5 below show the sorted correlations values between the left and right half of the
brain. For the variables, amusement and language it seems those elements have the greatest
correlation to the left half as even though the two start at the same magnitude of correlation in
both halves of the brain, there is not as much decay for these 2 variables in the left half of the
brain. For motion even though it would be possible to predict using either half, it seems using
the left half would be easier as the curve is much more smooth compared to the right half of the
brain. Looking at both sides of the brain, it seems amusement, attention, and environmental
sounds will be the most difficult to predict as the correlation values are much lower compared
to motion and language. But motion and language seem to be the easiest to predict as they
have quite a few locations in both sides of the brain where the correlation is over 0.5, which is
very promising to use for prediction. As all the graphs decay quite quickly for both sides of the
brain, in order to predict what variable is present accurately, it would be wise to only use 5-10
values in order to build a predictor. Below the figures is the code used to create these charts.

correlation.m
function [accuracy] = correlation(x,y)
%success is measured using the correlation between the true emotion
%verses the predicted emotion for the 5 emotions:
%Amusement, Attention, Environmental Sound, Language, Motion
x_bar = mean(x);
y_bar = mean(y);
x_diff = x - x_bar;
y_diff = y - y_bar;
accuracy = abs(sum(x_diff.*y_diff)/sqrt((sum(x_diff.^2))*sum(y_diff.^2)));
end
for i = 1:size(leftHalf,2)
for j = 1:5
accuracy_left(j,i) = correlation(leftHalf(:,i),Y(:,j));
end
end

end
for i = 1:size(rightHalf,2)

linearPredictor.m
function [prediction] = linearPredictor(x,y)
%function does basic linear regression to predict values
prediction = inv((x'*x))*x'*y;
end

4) We implement an SVM model using fitcecoc. The code to do this is shown below. Using the 6
values we obtained, we created an SVM, however this amount of data is not enough to train a
model using an SVM, so we are unable to calculate a correlation for the data set. Testing with 3
and 5 quantizer values we see that 5 performs better while 3 performs worse for variables
where this method works.
main.m
A = Y_amusement;
A_2 = merged_data_set_amusement;
cat_vals = zeros(800,1);
[columns,rows] = size(A_2);
for i = 1:columns
if A(i) >= 0 && A(i) <= 0.20
cat_vals(i) = 1;
elseif A(i) > 0.20 && A(i) <= 0.40
cat_vals(i) = 2;
elseif A(i) > 0.4 && A(i) <= 0.6
cat_vals(i) = 3;
elseif A(i) > 0.60 && A(i) <= 0.80
cat_vals(i) = 4;
else
cat_vals(i) = 5;
end
end
myModel = fitcecoc(A_2,cat_vals);
[predcat,score] = myModel.predict(A_2);
correlation_SVM_amusement = corr(A,predcat./4);

nonLinearPredictor.m
function[prediction] = nonLinearPredictor(x,y)
%function does basic non-linear squared regression to
predict values
x = x.^2;
prediction = inv((x'*x))*x'*y;
end

6) For the first part of trying a different predictor, an attempt was made to cube all the values of
the data set and then apply a linear regression. Unfortunately this did not get us better results,
and yet the results were worse than the linear or squared predictions. Correlations for doing this
for each predictee variable is shown in figures below as well as code used to do this. Compared
to the linear predictor we have a variance of approximately 0.0001 – 0.0004.

function[prediction] = nonLinearPredictor(x,y)

3 Conclusion
In this lab we found out ways to predict fMRI values for the predictee variables amusement, attention,
environmental sounds, language and motion. We investigated linear regression, SVM, and nonlinear
regression in order to implement a predictor for this data. In the end, we figured out that linear
regression and SVM was the best way to implement the predictor and gave the highest correlation. We
were able to improve the predictor by adjusting the number of columns used from the left and right side
of the brain to reach optimal correlation.
